article.headline: Irish post ninth straight win
article.linkText: Notre Dame blows 17-point lead but beats Hoyas
article.story:
SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) -- Notre Dame is having trouble focusing against lesser opponents.

The Irish (No. 7 ESPN/USA Today, No. 6 AP) nearly squandered a 17-point lead to Georgetown before beating the Hoyas 72-58 on Saturday for their ninth straight win.

"We were running our offense and doing whatever we wanted to do," said Jacqueline Batteast, who led the Irish with 20 points and eight rebounds. "Once we got the big lead, we lost the focus we had."

Against Providence, winless in the Big East, the Irish trailed by six points Wednesday before winning by 18.

Notre Dame (22-3, 10-2 Big East) led 31-14 and appeared headed for a blowout. But Georgetown (9-13, 4-7) cut the lead to 35-30 early in the second half. The Hoyas closed to 42-39 when Mary Lisicky hit a 3-pointer, and she closed the gap to 43-41 on a pair of free throws with 12:41 left.

Irish coach Muffet McGraw was disappointed the Irish let the Hoyas get back in the game.

"I didn't think we played as intelligently as we should have at times," McGraw said. "I just think we didn't make a lot of good decisions that we normally do."

The Irish regained their composure, though, after the Hoyas closed to two points. Batteast dribbled around a crowd in the lane and drove the baseline to spark a 17-4 run by the Irish. Batteast and Charel Allen scored six points each during the spurt. Megan Duffy, who had 17 points and seven assists, capped the run with a pair of free throws to give the Irish a 60-45 lead with 6:34 left.

Batteast moved into fourth place on Notre Dame's all-time scoring list with 1,765 points, two points ahead of Alicia Ratay. Ruth Riley, who led the Irish to a national championship in 2001, is third with 2,072 points.

Teresa Borton added 14 points and had a career-high 12 rebounds for her fourth career double-double as the Irish outrebounded Georgetown 42-21. Borton said the Irish have been working hard on improving their rebounding.

"It's been an issue all year long," she said. "All the coaches get on us for rebounds. That's what they say we need to do to win."

Lisicky led Georgetown with 16 points. Kate Carlin added 11 points and Bethany LeSueur had 10. Kieraah Marlow, Georgetown's leading scorer at 13.2 points a game, was held to six points.

Lisicky said the Hoyas can take solace in the way they fought back.

"Earlier in the year, if we had a 17-point deficit, we'd fold," Lisicky said. "We're more confident now than we were earlier in the year."

Georgetown coach Terri Williams-Flournoy said the rebounding advantage and 21 turnovers were too much to overcome.

"But we almost made up for it with our defense," she said. "We played 28 seconds of defense and in two seconds give up an offensive rebound."
